## Server side: configure the moth project

Preferred: the one-command setup flows (idempotent and re-runnable; they
diff current state, automate what Google/Apple expose via API, and print
exact console steps plus paste-back prompts for the rest — never a silent
skip). Both end with a verification checklist.

```sh
# Google: needs a GCP project, bundle/package ids, Android SHA fingerprints
moth setup google --project {{.Slug}}

# Apple: needs an App Store Connect API key (issuer id, key id, .p8 path)
moth setup apple --project {{.Slug}}
```

Alternative: declare the provider config in the project spec and
`moth project apply -f moth.yaml` (see
[cli-administration.md](cli-administration.md)), or fill the Providers
page in the admin SPA. Secrets (Google web client secret, Apple `.p8`
key) are write-only: reads only report `hasWebClientSecret` /
`hasPrivateKey`, and an empty secret on update keeps the stored value.

Afterwards verify end to end:

```sh
moth doctor --project {{.Slug}}
```

## App side: wire the native flows

`moth_auth` deliberately does not depend on `google_sign_in` or
`sign_in_with_apple`. Add them to the app and implement `MothOAuthAdapter`
(the SDK's example app ships this exact class to copy):

```dart
class AppOAuthAdapter implements MothOAuthAdapter {
  bool _googleInitialized = false;

  @override
  Future<MothGoogleCredential?> getGoogleIdToken(MothGoogleConfig config) async {
    final signIn = GoogleSignIn.instance;
    if (!_googleInitialized) {
      // Client IDs come from the project config — never hardcode them.
      await signIn.initialize(
        clientId: defaultTargetPlatform == TargetPlatform.iOS
            ? config.iosClientId
            : null,
        serverClientId: config.webClientId,
      );
      _googleInitialized = true;
    }
    final account = await signIn.authenticate();
    final idToken = account.authentication.idToken;
    if (idToken == null) return null;
    return MothGoogleCredential(idToken: idToken);
  }

  @override
  Future<MothAppleCredential?> getAppleCredential({required String hashedNonce}) async {
    final credential = await SignInWithApple.getAppleIDCredential(
      scopes: [AppleIDAuthorizationScopes.email, AppleIDAuthorizationScopes.fullName],
      nonce: hashedNonce, // moth verifies the nonce embedded in the token
    );
    final idToken = credential.identityToken;
    if (idToken == null) return null;
    return MothAppleCredential(
      idToken: idToken,
      authorizationCode: credential.authorizationCode,
      givenName: credential.givenName,   // only sent on first authorization
      familyName: credential.familyName,
    );
  }
}
```

Pass it to the app shell: `MothApp(oauthAdapter: AppOAuthAdapter(), ...)`.

Native setup the adapter needs:

- **Google / iOS**: add the reversed iOS client ID as a URL scheme in
  `ios/Runner/Info.plist` (`CFBundleURLSchemes`).
- **Google / Android**: register the app's SHA-1/SHA-256 fingerprints on
  the Android OAuth client (`moth setup google` walks through this;
  fingerprints come from `keytool` or the Play Console).
- **Apple / iOS**: enable the "Sign in with Apple" capability on the app
  target in Xcode; the app's bundle ID must be in the project's
  `settings.apple.bundleIds`.

## Failure modes

| Symptom | Fix |
| --- | --- |
| Provider button missing | Provider disabled in the project — enable it server-side (above) |
| Button says an adapter/setup is missing | Pass `oauthAdapter:` to `MothApp` and finish the native setup |
| Google returns no ID token | Client ID set mismatch — `serverClientId` must be the project's web client ID |
| `invalid provider token` from moth | Token `aud` not among the project's configured client IDs / bundle IDs; re-run `moth setup ...` or fix the project settings |
| Apple works on device, fails in moth | Nonce mismatch (pass `hashedNonce` through untouched) or bundle ID missing from `settings.apple.bundleIds` |
